{"parse":{"title":"Linga Bhairavi","pageid":53781590,"revid":813341499,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color:#FFC569\">Linga Bhairavi</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE,_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"SRI LINGA BHAIRAVI TEMPLE, SALEM - panoramio.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg/250px-SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"346\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg/375px-SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg/500px-SRI_LINGA_BHAIRAVI_TEMPLE%2C_SALEM_-_panoramio.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1592\" data-file-height=\"2202\" /></a><div>Linga Bhairavi</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Affiliation</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Devi\" title=\"Devi\">Devi</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/Mantra\" title=\"Mantra\">Mantra</a></th><td>\nLinga Bhairavi Stuti</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Festivals</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Thaipusam\" title=\"Thaipusam\">Thaipusam</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Navratri\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navratri\">Navratri</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Dussehra\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Dussehra\">Dussehra</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Linga Bhairavi</b> is a form of the mother goddess, associated with <a href=\"/wiki/Dhyanalinga\" title=\"Dhyanalinga\">Dhyanalinga</a>, with temples at the <a href=\"/wiki/Velliangiri_Mountains\" title=\"Velliangiri Mountains\">Velliangiri Mountains</a> near <a href=\"/wiki/Coimbatore\" title=\"Coimbatore\">Coimbatore</a>, and in <a href=\"/wiki/Salem,_Tamil_Nadu\" title=\"Salem, Tamil Nadu\">Salem, Tamil Nadu</a>. The Linga Bhairavi <a href=\"/wiki/Yantra\" title=\"Yantra\">yantra</a> and Linga Bhairavi Avighna yantra are associated with her.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Etymology\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Etymology</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Temples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Temples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Rituals\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Rituals</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Festivals\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Festivals</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">7</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Etymology\">Etymology</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Etymology\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Sanskrit word \"<a href=\"/wiki/Bhairavi\" title=\"Bhairavi\">Bhairavi</a>\" means \"fierce one\" and is the feminine counterpart of \"<a href=\"/wiki/Bhairava\" title=\"Bhairava\">Bhairava</a>\", a fierce manifestation of Shiva.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The word \"<a href=\"/wiki/Lingam\" title=\"Lingam\">linga</a>\" refers to the Devi, who is in the form of a linga.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Temples\">Temples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Temples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The primary Linga Bhairavi temples are at the Velliangiri foothills and at Salem in Tamil Nadu. The temple at Velliangiri was built in January 2010 by <a href=\"/wiki/Sadhguru\" title=\"Sadhguru\">Sadhguru</a>. The consecration was completed on the day of <a href=\"/wiki/Thaipusam\" title=\"Thaipusam\">Thaipusam</a> on January 30.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The temple was visited by the <a href=\"/wiki/Prime_Minister_of_India\" title=\"Prime Minister of India\">Prime Minister of India</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Narendra_Modi\" title=\"Narendra Modi\">Narendra Modi</a> on <a href=\"/wiki/Maha_Shivaratri\" title=\"Maha Shivaratri\">Maha Shivaratri</a>, 2017.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The temple at Salem, also built by Sadhguru, was completed in 2014. Two kinds of Linga Bhairavi yantras are present.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> They are designed as a copper plate, square in shape, upon which the yantra's geometry is inscribed. A stone linga of the Devi is placed on top of the yantra.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Rituals\">Rituals</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Rituals\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Several rituals are practiced at Linga Bhairavi temples, primarily related to health, marriage, children and relationships.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Rituals such as <a href=\"/wiki/%C5%9Ar%C4%81ddha\" title=\"\u015ar\u0101ddha\">\u015ar\u0101ddha</a> for the recently deceased and for ancestors are also practiced at the temple, as well as at crematoriums in nearby areas.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> These rituals are called Kala Bhairava Karma, and invoke <a href=\"/wiki/Kalabhairava\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kalabhairava\">Kalabhairava</a>, a form of Shiva.\n</p><p><a href=\"/wiki/Sudha_Ragunathan\" title=\"Sudha Ragunathan\">Sudha Ragunathan</a> released a music album in 2011 titled <i>Linga Bhairavi</i>, in honour of Linga Bhairavi. The album was released by <a href=\"/wiki/Amutham_Music\" title=\"Amutham Music\">Amutham Music</a> and includes songs such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Ashtakam\" title=\"Ashtakam\">ashtakam</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Sindhu_Bhairavi_(raga)\" title=\"Sindhu Bhairavi (raga)\">Sindhu Bhairavi</a>, and a <a href=\"/wiki/Ragamalika\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ragamalika\">ragamalika</a> in the ragas <a href=\"/wiki/Bhairavi_(Hindustani)\" title=\"Bhairavi (Hindustani)\">Bhairavi</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Anandabhairavi\" title=\"Anandabhairavi\">Anandabhairavi</a> and Sindhu Bhairavi. The album's last song is titled <i>Arathi</i>, which seeks the goddess' blessings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Festivals\">Festivals</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Festivals\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The festivals celebrated at the Linga Bhairavi temple include <a href=\"/wiki/Maha_Shivaratri\" title=\"Maha Shivaratri\">Maha Shivaratri</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Navratri\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navratri\">Navratri</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> and Thaipusam.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> A few days before Maha Shivaratri, the music festival <a href=\"/wiki/Yaksha_(festival)\" title=\"Yaksha (festival)\">Yaksha</a> is celebrated at the Velliangiri temple, featuring Indian classical music and dance performances. Performers have included <a href=\"/wiki/Jasraj\" title=\"Jasraj\">Pandit Jasraj</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hariprasad_Chaurasia\" title=\"Hariprasad Chaurasia\">Pandit Hariprasad Chaurasia</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Alarmel_Valli\" title=\"Alarmel Valli\">Alarmel Valli</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Amjad_Ali_Khan\" title=\"Amjad Ali Khan\">Amjad Ali Khan</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Navratri celebrations at the temple also include performing arts and Indian classical music and dance. Local <a href=\"/wiki/Folk_art\" title=\"Folk art\">folk arts</a> are also featured at the ten-day festival, which ends on <a href=\"/wiki/Vijayadashami\" title=\"Vijayadashami\">Vijayadashami</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> A special Navratri procession of the Devi is taken from the temple, till Dhyanalinga. This procession takes place every <a href=\"/wiki/Purnima\" title=\"Purnima\">Purnima</a> or full moon as well.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Dhyanalinga\" title=\"Dhyanalinga\">Dhyanalinga</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Bhairavi\" title=\"Bhairavi\">Bhairavi</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Linga_Bhairavi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780198610250.001.0001/acref-9780198610250\"><i>Dictionary of Hinduism - Oxford Reference</i></a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1093/acref/9780198610250.001.0001\">10.1093/acref/9780198610250.001.0001</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Dictionary+of+Hinduism+-+Oxford+Reference&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1093%2Facref%2F9780198610250.001.0001&amp;r